  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q081.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.81 a.6 — Should religion be preferred to the other moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.religion</data>
  <data key="d12">Religion</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q081-a006-treated-in-concept-religion-st-ii-ii-q081-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q081.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">moral virtues , as stated above ( Article 5 ; II-II:4:7 ), are about matters that are ordered to God as their end. And religion approaches nearer to God than the other moral virtues , in so far as its actions are directly and immediately ordered to the honor of God . Hence religion exce</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q081.a007" target="concept.religion" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q081.a007.treated_in.concept.religion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q081.a007.treated_in.concept.religion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q081.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.81 a.7 — Does religion have any external actions?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.religion</data>
  <data key="d12">Religion</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q081-a007-treated-in-concept-religion-st-ii-ii-q081-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q081.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">used thereby, as by signs, to the spiritual acts by means of which he is united to God . Therefore the internal acts of religion take precedence of the others and belong to religion essentially , while its external acts are secondary, and subordinate to the internal acts.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
