  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Devotion is derived from "devote" [The Latin 'devovere' means 'to vow ']; wherefore those persons are said to be "devout" who, in a way, devote themselves to God , so a</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082" target="st.ii-ii.q082.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 — Devotion</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q082.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.82 a.1 — Is devotion a special act?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that devotion is not a special act. That which qualifies other acts is seemingly not a special act. Now devotion seems to qualify other acts, for it is written ( 2 Chronicles 29:31 ): "All the multitude off</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082" target="st.ii-ii.q082.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 — Devotion</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q082.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.82 a.2 — Is it an act of religion?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that devotion is not an act of religion. Devotion, as stated above ( Article 1 ), consists in giving oneself up to God . But this is done chiefly by charity , since according to Dionysius (Div. Nom. iv) "th</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082" target="st.ii-ii.q082.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 — Devotion</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q082.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.82 a.3 — What is the cause of devotion?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that contemplation or meditation is not the cause of devotion. No cause hinders its effect. But subtle considerations about abstract matters are often a hindrance to devotion. Therefore contemplation or med</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082" target="st.ii-ii.q082.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q082.contains.st.ii-ii.q082.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 — Devotion</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q082.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.82 a.4 — Its effect?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that joy is not an effect of devotion. As stated above ( Article 3, Reply to Objection 2 ), Christ's Passion is the chief incentive to devotion. But the consideration thereof causes an affliction of the sou</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082.a001" target="concept.devotion" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a001.treated_in.concept.devotion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a001.treated_in.concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 a.1 — Is devotion a special act?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d12">Devotion</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q082-a001-treated-in-concept-devotion-st-ii-ii-q082-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Devotion is derived from "devote" [The Latin 'devovere' means 'to vow ']; wherefore those persons are said to be "devout" who, in a way, devote themselves to God , so a</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082.a002" target="concept.devotion" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a002.treated_in.concept.devotion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a002.treated_in.concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 a.2 — Is it an act of religion?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d12">Devotion</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q082-a002-treated-in-concept-devotion-st-ii-ii-q082-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">it belongs to that virtue to have the will ready to do such things, and this is to be devout. Hence it is evident that devotion is an act of religion.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082.a003" target="concept.devotion" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a003.treated_in.concept.devotion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a003.treated_in.concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 a.3 — What is the cause of devotion?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d12">Devotion</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q082-a003-treated-in-concept-devotion-st-ii-ii-q082-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The extrinsic and chief cause of devotion is God , of Whom Ambrose , commenting on Luke 9:55 , says that " God calls whom He deigns to call, and whom He wills He makes religious: the profane Samaritans</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q082.a004" target="concept.devotion" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a004.treated_in.concept.devotion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q082.a004.treated_in.concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q082.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.82 a.4 — Its effect?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.devotion</data>
  <data key="d12">Devotion</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q082-a004-treated-in-concept-devotion-st-ii-ii-q082-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q082.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The direct and principal effect of devotion is the spiritual joy of the mind , though sorrow is its secondary and indirect effect. For it has been stated ( Article 3 ) that devotion is caused by a twofol</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="concept.prayer" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q083.treated_in.concept.prayer">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q083.treated_in.concept.prayer</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prayer</data>
  <data key="d12">Prayer</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q083-treated-in-concept-prayer-st-ii-ii-q083-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">According to Cassiodorus [Comment. in Psalm 38:13 " prayer [oratio] is spoken reason [oris ratio]." Now the speculative and practical reason differ in this, that the speculative merely apprehends its object, whereas th</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.1 — Is prayer an act of the appetitive or of the cognitive power?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that prayer is an act of the appetitive power. It belongs to prayer to be heard. Now it is the desire that is heard by God , according to Psalm 9:38 , "The Lord hath heard the desire of the poor." Therefore</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.2 — Is it fitting to pray to God?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is unbecoming to pray . Prayer seems to be necessary in order that we may make our needs known to the person to whom we pray . But according to Matthew 6:32 , "Your Father knoweth that you have need</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.3 — Is prayer an act of religion?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that prayer is not an act of religion. Since religion is a part of justice , it resides in the will as in its subject. But prayer belongs to the intellective part, as stated above ( Article 1 ). Therefore p</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.4 — Should we pray to God alone?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we ought to pray to God alone. Prayer is an act of religion, as stated above ( Article 3 ). But God alone is to be worshiped by religion. Therefore we should pray to God alone.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.5 — Should we ask for something definite when we pray?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we ought not to ask for anything definite when we pray to God . According to Damascene (De Fide Orth. iii, 24), "to pray is to ask becoming things of God "; wherefore it is useless to pray for what is </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.6 — Should we ask for temporal things when we pray?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that man ought not to ask God for temporal things when he prays . We seek what we ask for in prayer . But we should not seek for temporal things, for it is written ( Matthew 6:33 ): "Seek ye . . . first the</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.7 — Should we pray for others?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we ought not to pray for others. On praying we ought to conform to the pattern given by our Lord . Now in the Lord's Prayer we make petitions for ourselves, not for others; thus we say: "Give us this d</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.8 — Should we pray for our enemies?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we ought not to pray for our enemies. According to Romans 15:4 , "what things soever were written, were written for our learning." Now Holy Writ contains many imprecations against enemies; thus it is w</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.9 — The seven petitions of the Lord's Prayer</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a009.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the seven petitions of the Lord's Prayer are not fittingly assigned. It is useless to ask for that to be hallowed which is always holy . But the name of God is always holy , according to Luke 1:49 , "H</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.10 — Is prayer proper to the rational creature?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a010.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that prayer is not proper to the rational creature. Asking and receiving apparently belong to the same subject. But receiving is becoming also to uncreated Persons, viz. the Son and Holy Ghost . Therefore i</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a011">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a011</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a011</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.11 — Do the saints in heaven pray for us?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a011.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the saints in heaven do not pray for us. A man's action is more meritorious for himself than for others. But the saints in heaven do not merit for themselves, neither do they pray for themselves, since</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a012" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a012">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a012</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a012</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.12 — Should prayer be vocal?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a012.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that prayer ought not to be vocal. As stated above ( Article 4 ), prayer is addressed chiefly to God . Now God knows the language of the heart. Therefore it is useless to employ vocal prayer .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a013" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a013">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a013</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a013</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.13 — Is attention requisite in prayer?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a013.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that attention is a necessary condition of prayer . It is written ( John 4:24 ): " God is a spirit, and they that adore Him must adore Him in spirit and in truth ." But prayer is not in spirit unless it be </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a014" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a014">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a014</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a014</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.14 — Should prayer last a long time?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a014.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that prayer should not be continual. It is written ( Matthew 6:7 ): "When you are praying , speak not much." Now one who prays a long time needs to speak much, especially if his be vocal prayer . Therefore </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a015" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a015">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a015</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a015</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.15 — Is prayer meritorious?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a015.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that prayer is not meritorious . All merit proceeds from grace . But prayer precedes grace , since even grace is obtained by means of prayer according to Luke 11:13 , "(How much more) will your Father from </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
