  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As Augustine says (ad Probam, de orando Deum, Ep. cxxx, 12): "It is lawful to pray for what it is lawful to desire." Now it is lawful to desire temporal things, not indeed principally, by placing our end therein, but as helps whereby we are assisted in tending</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083.a007" target="concept.prayer" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q083.a007.treated_in.concept.prayer">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q083.a007.treated_in.concept.prayer</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 a.7 — Should we pray for others?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prayer</data>
  <data key="d12">Prayer</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q083-a007-treated-in-concept-prayer-st-ii-ii-q083-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">. John Chrysostom ]: " Necessity binds us to pray for ourselves, fraternal charity urges us to pray for others: and the prayer that fraternal charity proffers is sweeter to God than that which is the outcome of necessity ."</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
