</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q087.a002" target="concept.tithes" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q087.a002.treated_in.concept.tithes">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q087.a002.treated_in.concept.tithes</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q087.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.87 a.2 — Of what things ought tithes to be paid?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.tithes</data>
  <data key="d12">Tithes</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q087-a002-treated-in-concept-tithes-st-ii-ii-q087-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q087.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">In judging about a thing we should look to its principle. Now the principle of the payment of tithes is the debt whereby carnal things are due to those who sow spiritual things, according to the saying of the Apostle ( 1 Corinthians 9:11 ), "If we have sown un</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q087.a003" target="concept.tithes" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q087.a003.treated_in.concept.tithes">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q087.a003.treated_in.concept.tithes</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q087.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.87 a.3 — To whom ought they to be paid?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.tithes</data>
  <data key="d12">Tithes</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q087-a003-treated-in-concept-tithes-st-ii-ii-q087-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q087.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Two things have to be considered with regard to tithes : namely, the right to receive tithes , and the things given in the name of tithes . The right to receive tithes is a spiritual thing, for it arises from the d</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q087.a004" target="concept.tithes" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q087.a004.treated_in.concept.tithes">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q087.a004.treated_in.concept.tithes</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q087.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.87 a.4 — Who ought to pay tithes?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.tithes</data>
  <data key="d12">Tithes</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q087-a004-treated-in-concept-tithes-st-ii-ii-q087-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q087.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">is giver and receiver, even as agent and patient, on account of different causes and from different points of view. Now tithes are due to the clergy as being ministers of the altar and sowers of spiritual things among the people. Wherefore those members of the clergy as such, i.e. as h</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.treated_in.concept.vow">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q088.treated_in.concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">A vow denotes a binding to do or omit some particular thing. Now one man binds himself to another by means of a promise, which is an act of the reason to which facul</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.1 — What is a vow?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a vow consists in nothing but a purpose of the will . According to some [ William of Auxerre , Sum. Aur. III, xxviii, qu. 1; Albertus Magnus , Sent. iv, D, 38, "a vow is a conception of a good purpose </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.2 — What is the matter of a vow?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a vow need not be always about a better good . A greater good is one that pertains to supererogation. But vows are not only about matters of supererogation, but also about matters of salvation : thus i</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.3 — The obligation of vows</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that vows are not all binding. For man needs things that are done by another, more than God does, since He has no need for our goods ( Psalm 15:2 ). Now according to the prescription of human laws [Dig. L. </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.4 — The use of taking vows</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not expedient to take vows . It is not expedient to anyone to deprive himself of the good that God has given him. Now one of the greatest goods that God has given man is liberty whereof he seems </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.5 — Of what virtue is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a vow is not an act of latria or religion. Every act of virtue is matter for a vow . Now it would seem to pertain to the same virtue to promise a thing and to do it. Therefore a vow pertains to any vir</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.6 — Is it more meritorious to do a thing from a vow, than without a vow?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is more praiseworthy and meritorious to do a thing without a vow than in fulfilment of a vow . Prosper says (De Vita Contempl. ii): "We should abstain or fast without putting ourselves under the nec</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.7 — The solemnizing of a vow</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a vow is not solemnized by the reception of holy orders and by the profession of a certain rule. As stated above ( Article 1 ), a vow is a promise made to God . Now external actions pertaining to solem</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.8 — Can those who are under another's power take vows?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that those who are subject to another's power are not hindered from taking vows . The lesser bond is surpassed by the greater. Now the obligation of one man subject to another is a lesser bond than a vow wh</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.9 — May children be bound by vow to enter religion?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a009.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that children cannot bind themselves by vow to enter religion. Since a vow requires deliberation of the mind , it is fitting that those alone should vow who have the use of reason . But this is lacking in c</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 — Vows</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q088.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.88 a.10 — Is a vow subject to dispensation or commutation?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a010.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that vows are not subject to dispensation. It is less to have a vow commuted than to be dispensed from keeping it. But a vow cannot be commuted, according to Leviticus 27:9-10 , "A beast that may be sacrifi</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088" target="st.ii-ii.q088.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q088.contains.st.ii-ii.q088.a011">
