  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.5 — Of what virtue is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a005-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">to the service of God is the proper act of latria . Now, it is evident from what has been said above ( 1 and 2 ) that a vow is a promise made to God , and that a promise is nothing else than a directing of the thing promised to the person to whom the promise is made. Hence a vow is</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088.a006" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a006.treated_in.concept.vow">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a006.treated_in.concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.6 — Is it more meritorious to do a thing from a vow, than without a vow?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a006-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">For three reasons it is better and more meritorious to do one and the same deed with a vow than without. First, because to vow , as stated above ( Article 5 ) is an act of religion which is the chief of the moral virtues . Now the more excellent the</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088.a007" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a007.treated_in.concept.vow">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a007.treated_in.concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.7 — The solemnizing of a vow</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a007-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e is solemnized in another way, namely, the array of the bridegroom and bride and the gathering of their kindred. Now a vow is a promise made to God : wherefore, the solemnization of a vow consists in something spiritual pertaining to God ; i.e. in some spiritual blessing or consecr</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088.a008" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a008.treated_in.concept.vow">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a008.treated_in.concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.8 — Can those who are under another's power take vows?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a008-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ), a vow is a promise made to God . Now no man can firmly bind himself by a promise to do what is in another's power, but only to that which is entirely in his own powe</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088.a009" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a009.treated_in.concept.vow">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a009.treated_in.concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.9 — May children be bound by vow to enter religion?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a009-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As may be gathered from what has been said above ( Article 7 ), vows are of two kinds, simple and solemn . And since, as stated in the same article, the solemnization of a vow consists in a spiritual blessing and consecration b</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088.a010" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a010.treated_in.concept.vow">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a010.treated_in.concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.10 — Is a vow subject to dispensation or commutation?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a010-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a010-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The dispensation from a vow is to be taken in the same sense as a dispensation given in the observance of a law because, as stated above ( I-II:96:6 ; I-II:97:4 ), a law is made with an e</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088.a011" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a011.treated_in.concept.vow">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a011.treated_in.concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.11 — Can a dispensation be granted in a solemn vow of continence?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a011-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a011-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Three things may be considered in a solemn vow of continency : first, the matter of the vow , namely, continency ; secondly, the perpetuity of the vow , namely, when a person binds himself by vow to the per</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q088.a012" target="concept.vow" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q088.a012.treated_in.concept.vow">
