  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q088.a012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.88 a.12 — Is the authority of a superior required in a dispensation from a vow?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vow</data>
  <data key="d12">Vow</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q088-a012-treated-in-concept-vow-st-ii-ii-q088-a012-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q088.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( 1 and 2 ), a vow is a promise made to God about something acceptable to Him. Now if you promise something to anyone it depends on his decision whether he accept what you promis</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As the Apostle says ( Hebrews 6:16 ), oaths are taken for the purpose of confirmation. Now speculative propositions receive confirmation from reason, which proceeds from principles known naturally and i</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.1 — What is an oath?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that to swear is not to call God to witness. Whoever invokes the authority of Holy Writ calls God to witness, since it is His word that Holy Writ contains. Therefore, if to swear is to call God to witness, </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.2 — Is it lawful?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not lawful to swear. Nothing forbidden in the Divine Law is lawful. Now swearing is forbidden ( Matthew 5:34 ), "But I say to you not to swear at all"; and ( James 5:12 ), "Above all things, my b</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.3 — What are the accompanying conditions of an oath?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that justice , judgment and truth are unsuitably assigned as the conditions accompanying an oath . Things should not be enumerated as diverse, if one of them includes the other. Now of these three, one incl</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.4 — Of what virtue is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that an oath is not an act of religion, or latria . Acts of religion are about holy and divine things. But oaths are employed in connection with human disputes, as the Apostle declares ( Hebrews 6:16 ). The</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.5 — Are oaths desirable, and should they be employed frequently as something useful and good?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that oaths are desirable and to be used frequently as something useful and good . Just as a vow is an act of religion, so is an oath . Now it is commendable and more meritorious to do a thing by vow , becau</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.6 — Is it lawful to swear by a creature?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not lawful to swear by creatures. It is written ( Matthew 5:34-36 ): "I say to you not to swear at all, neither by heaven . . . nor by the earth . . . nor by Jerusalem . . . nor by thy head": and</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.7 — Is an oath binding?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that an oath has no binding force. An oath is employed in order to confirm the truth of an assertion. But when a person makes an assertion about the future his assertion is true , though it may not be verif</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.8 — Which is more binding, an oath or a vow?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that an oath is more binding than a vow . A vow is a simple promise: whereas an oath includes, besides a promise, an appeal to God as witness. Therefore an oath is more binding than a vow .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.9 — Is an oath subject to dispensation?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a009.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that no one can dispense from an oath . Just as truth is required for a declaratory oath , which is about the past or the present, so too is it required for a promissory oath , which is about the future. No</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089" target="st.ii-ii.q089.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q089.contains.st.ii-ii.q089.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 — Oaths</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q089.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.89 a.10 — Who may lawfully swear, and when?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a010.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that an oath is not voided by a condition of person or time. An oath , according to the Apostle ( Hebrews 6:16 ), is employed for the purpose of confirmation. Now it is competent to anyone to confirm his as</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a001" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a001.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a001.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.1 — What is an oath?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a001-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As the Apostle says ( Hebrews 6:16 ), oaths are taken for the purpose of confirmation. Now speculative propositions receive confirmation from reason, which proceeds from principles known naturally and i</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a001" target="concept.sworn_assertion" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a001.treated_in.concept.sworn_assertion">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a001.treated_in.concept.sworn_assertion</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.1 — What is an oath?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sworn_assertion</data>
  <data key="d12">Sworn Assertion</data>
  <data key="d13">object</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a001-treated-in-concept-sworn-assertion-st-ii-ii-q089-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As the Apostle says ( Hebrews 6:16 ), oaths are taken for the purpose of confirmation. Now speculative propositions receive confirmation from reason, which proceeds from principles known naturally and infallibly true . But particular contingent</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a002" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a002.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a002.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.2 — Is it lawful?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a002-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">judgment to himself" ( 1 Corinthians 11:29 ). Accordingly in answer to the question in point it must be stated that an oath is in itself lawful and commendable. This is proved from its origin and from its end. From its origin, because swearing owes its introduction to the faith wher</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a003" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a003.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a003.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.3 — What are the accompanying conditions of an oath?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a003-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 2 ), an oath is not good except for one who makes good use of it. Now two conditions are required for the good use of an oath . First, that one swear, not for frivolous, bu</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a004" target="concept.divine_name" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a004.treated_in.concept.divine_name">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a004.treated_in.concept.divine_name</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.4 — Of what virtue is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divine_name</data>
  <data key="d12">Divine Name</data>
  <data key="d13">object</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a004-treated-in-concept-divine-name-st-ii-ii-q089-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As appears from what has been said above ( Article 1 ), he that swears calls God to witness in confirmation of what he says. Now nothing is confirmed save by what is more certain and more powerful. Therefore in the very fact that a man swea</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a004" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a004.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a004.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.4 — Of what virtue is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a004-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">o give very great honor ." Now to show reverence to God belongs to religion or latria . wherefore it is evident that an oath is an act of religion or latria .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a005" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a005.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a005.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.5 — Are oaths desirable, and should they be employed frequently as something useful and good?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a005-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ong those that are necessary : this is clear in the case of medicine which is required as a remedy for sickness. Now an oath is required as a remedy to a defect, namely, some man's lack of belief in another man . Wherefore an oath is not to be reckoned among those things that are des</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a006" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a006.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a006.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.6 — Is it lawful to swear by a creature?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a006-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3 ), there are two kinds of oath . One is uttered a simple contestation or calling God as witness: and this kind of oath , like faith , is based on God's truth . Now faith is essentially and c</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a007" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a007.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a007.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.7 — Is an oath binding?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a007-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">An obligation implies something to be done or omitted; so that apparently it regards neither the declaratory oath (which is about something present or past), nor such oaths as are about something to be effected by some other cause (as, for example, if one were to swear tha</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a008" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a008.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a008.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.8 — Which is more binding, an oath or a vow?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a008-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The obligation both of vow and of an oath arises from something Divine; but in different ways. For the obligation of a vow arises from the fidelity we owe God , which binds us to fulfil our promises to</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q089.a009" target="concept.oath" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a009.treated_in.concept.oath">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q089.a009.treated_in.concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q089.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.89 a.9 — Is an oath subject to dispensation?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.oath</data>
  <data key="d12">Oath</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q089-a009-treated-in-concept-oath-st-ii-ii-q089-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q089.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">uch a case comes under neither law nor vow . Now anything morally evil or hurtful is incompatible with the matter of an oath : for if it be morally evil it is opposed to justice , and if it be hurtful it is contrary to judgment. Therefore an oath likewise admits of dispensation.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
