  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">celebrated by the pontiffs in the temples [De Civ. Dei vi, 5. Now all these come under the head of the superstition of idolatry . Wherefore Augustine says (De Doctr. Christ. ii, 20): "Anything invented by man for making and worshipping idols , or for giving Divine worship to a creature</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q094" target="st.ii-ii.q094.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q094</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.94 — Idolatry</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q094.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.94 a.1 — Is idolatry a species of superstition?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q094.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that idolatry is not rightly reckoned a species of superstition. Just as heretics are unbelievers, so are idolaters. But heresy is a species of unbelief, as stated above ( II-II:11:1 ). Therefore idolatry i</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q094" target="st.ii-ii.q094.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q094</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.94 — Idolatry</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q094.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.94 a.2 — Is it a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q094.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that idolatry is not a sin . Nothing is a sin that the true faith employs in worshipping God . Now the true faith employs images for the divine worship: since both in the Tabernacle were there images of the</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q094" target="st.ii-ii.q094.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q094</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.94 — Idolatry</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q094.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.94 a.3 — Is it the gravest sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q094.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that idolatry is not the gravest of sins . The worst is opposed to the best (Ethic. viii, 10). But interior worship, which consists of faith , hope and charity , is better than external worship. Therefore u</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q094" target="st.ii-ii.q094.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q094.contains.st.ii-ii.q094.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q094</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.94 — Idolatry</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q094.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.94 a.4 — The cause of this sin</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q094.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the cause of idolatry was not on the part of man . On man there is nothing but either nature , virtue , or guilt. But the cause of idolatry could not be on the part of man's nature , since rather does </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
