  <data key="d17">celebrated by the pontiffs in the temples [De Civ. Dei vi, 5. Now all these come under the head of the superstition of idolatry . Wherefore Augustine says (De Doctr. Christ. ii, 20): "Anything invented by man for making and worshipping idols , or for giving Divine worship to a creature</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q094.a002" target="concept.idolatry" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q094.a002.treated_in.concept.idolatry">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q094.a002.treated_in.concept.idolatry</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q094.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.94 a.2 — Is it a sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.idolatry</data>
  <data key="d12">Idolatry</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q094-a002-treated-in-concept-idolatry-st-ii-ii-q094-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q094.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">There has been a twofold error in this matter. For some [The School of Plato ] have thought that to offer sacrifices and other things pertaining to latria, not only to God but also to the others aforesaid, is due and good in itself, since they held that divine</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q094.a003" target="concept.idolatry" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q094.a003.treated_in.concept.idolatry">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q094.a003.treated_in.concept.idolatry</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q094.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.94 a.3 — Is it the gravest sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.idolatry</data>
  <data key="d12">Idolatry</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q094-a003-treated-in-concept-idolatry-st-ii-ii-q094-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q094.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The gravity of a sin may be considered in two ways. First, on the part of the sin itself, and thus idolatry is the most grievous sin . For just as the most heinous crime in an earthly commonwealth would seem to be for a man to give royal honor to another than the tru</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q094.a004" target="concept.idolatry" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q094.a004.treated_in.concept.idolatry">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q094.a004.treated_in.concept.idolatry</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q094.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.94 a.4 — The cause of this sin</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.idolatry</data>
  <data key="d12">Idolatry</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q094-a004-treated-in-concept-idolatry-st-ii-ii-q094-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q094.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Idolatry had a twofold cause . One was a dispositive cause ; this was on the part of man , and in three ways. First, on account of his inordinate affections, forasmuch</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Divination denotes a foretelling of the future. The future may be foreknown in two ways: first in its causes , secondly in itself. Now the causes of the future are threef</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.1 — Is divination a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that divination is not a sin . Divination is derived from something "divine": and things that are divine pertain to holiness rather than to sin . Therefore it seems that divination is not a sin .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.2 — Is it a species of superstition?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that divination is not a species of superstition . The same thing cannot be a species of diverse genera. Now divination is apparently a species of curiosity, according to Augustine (De Vera Relig. xxxviii) </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.3 — The species of divination</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we should not distinguish several species of divination . Where the formality of sin is the same, there are not seemingly several species of sin . Now there is one formality of sin in all divinations, </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.4 — Divination by means of demons</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that divination practiced by invoking the demons is not unlawful. Christ did nothing unlawful, according to 1 Peter 2:22 , "Who did no sin ." Yet our Lord asked the demon : "What is thy name?" and the latte</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.5 — Divination by the stars</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that divination by the stars is not unlawful. It is lawful to foretell effects by observing their causes : thus a physician foretells death from the disposition of the disease. Now the heavenly bodies are t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.6 — Divination by dreams</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that divination by dreams is not unlawful. It is not unlawful to make use of divine instruction. Now men are instructed by God in dreams, for it is written ( Job 33:15-16 ): "By a dream in a vision by night</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.7 — Divination by auguries and like observances</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that divination by auguries, omens, and by like observations of external things is not unlawful. If it were unlawful holy men would not make use thereof. Now we read of Joseph that he paid attention to augu</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095" target="st.ii-ii.q095.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q095.contains.st.ii-ii.q095.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 — Superstition in divinations</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q095.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.95 a.8 — Divination by lots</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that divination by drawing lots is not unlawful, because a gloss of Augustine on Psalm 30:16 , "My lots are in Thy hands," says: "It is not wrong to cast lots, for it is a means of ascertaining the divine w</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a001" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a001.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a001.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.1 — Is divination a sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a001-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Divination denotes a foretelling of the future. The future may be foreknown in two ways: first in its causes , secondly in itself. Now the causes of the future are threef</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a002" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a002.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a002.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.2 — Is it a species of superstition?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a002-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">offered to demons , but also recourse to the help of the demons for the purpose of doing or knowing something. But all divination results from the demons ' operation, either because the demons are expressly invoked that the future may be made known , or because the demons thrust themselve</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a003" target="concept.astrological_divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.astrological_divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.astrological_divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.3 — The species of divination</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.astrological_divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Astrological Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a003-treated-in-concept-astrological-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">rtain things. If one endeavor to know the future by observing the position and movements of the stars, this belongs to "astrologers," who are also called "genethliacs," because they take note of the days on which people are born. If one observe the movements and cries of birds or of any ani</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a003" target="concept.augury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.augury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.augury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.3 — The species of divination</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.augury</data>
  <data key="d12">Augury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a003-treated-in-concept-augury-st-ii-ii-q095-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ries of birds or of any animals, or the sneezing of men , or the sudden movements of limbs, this belongs in general to "augury," which is so called from the chattering of birds [avium garritu], just as "auspice" is derived from watching birds [avium inspectione]. These are chiefly wont</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a003" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.3 — The species of divination</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a003-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 2 ), all divinations seek to acquire foreknowledge of future events, by means of some counsel and help of a demon , who is either expressly called upon to give his help, or else t</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a003" target="concept.divination_by_demons" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.divination_by_demons">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.divination_by_demons</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.3 — The species of divination</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination_by_demons</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination by Demons</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a003-treated-in-concept-divination-by-demons-st-ii-ii-q095-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">alled " divination by dreams": sometimes they employ apparitions or utterances of the dead, and this species is called "necromancy," for as Isidore observes (Etym. viii) in Greek, nekron "means dead and manteia divination , because after certain incantations and the sprinkling of blood, th</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a003" target="concept.divination_by_dreams" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.divination_by_dreams">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.divination_by_dreams</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.3 — The species of divination</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination_by_dreams</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination by Dreams</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a003-treated-in-concept-divination-by-dreams-st-ii-ii-q095-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">igiation" because man's eyes are blindfolded [praestringuntur]. Sometimes they make use of dreams, and this is called " divination by dreams": sometimes they employ apparitions or utterances of the dead, and this species is called "necromancy," for as Isidore observes (Etym. viii) in Greek, nekron "</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a003" target="concept.sortilege" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.sortilege">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a003.treated_in.concept.sortilege</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.3 — The species of divination</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.sortilege</data>
  <data key="d12">Sortilege</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a003-treated-in-concept-sortilege-st-ii-ii-q095-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">rving who throws the highest score; or by observing what catches the eye when one opens a book, all of which are named "sortilege." Accordingly it is clear that there are three kinds of divination . The first is when the demons are invoked openly, this comes under the head of "necromancy"</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a004" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a004.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a004.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.4 — Divination by means of demons</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a004-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">All divination by invoking demons is unlawful for two reasons. The first is gathered from the principle of divination , which is a compact made expressly with a demon by the</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a005" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a005.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a005.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.5 — Divination by the stars</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a005-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( 1 and 2 ), the operation of the demon thrusts itself into those divinations which are based on false and vain opinions, in order that man's mind may become entangled in vanity and falsehood. Now one makes use of a vain and false opini</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a006" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a006.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a006.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.6 — Divination by dreams</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a006-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( A2 , Article 6 ), divination is superstitious and unlawful when it is based on a false opinion. Wherefore we must consider what is true in the matter of foreknowing the future from dreams.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a007" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a007.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a007.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.7 — Divination by auguries and like observances</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a007-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">g to divine providence and sometimes according to the action of the demons . Accordingly we must say that all such like divinations are superstitious and unlawful, if they be extended beyond the limits set according to the order of nature or of divine providence .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q095.a008" target="concept.divination" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a008.treated_in.concept.divination">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q095.a008.treated_in.concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q095.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.95 a.8 — Divination by lots</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.divination</data>
  <data key="d12">Divination</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q095-a008-treated-in-concept-divination-st-ii-ii-q095-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q095.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">one, it is called "sortilege of consultation"; if one seeks to know what is going to happen, it is called "sortilege of divination ." Now the actions of man that are required for sortilege and their results are not subject to the dispositions of the stars. Wherefore if anyone practicing so</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q096" target="concept.superstitious_observance" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q096.treated_in.concept.superstitious_observance">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q096.treated_in.concept.superstitious_observance</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q096</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.96 — Superstition in observances</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.superstitious_observance</data>
  <data key="d12">Superstitious Observance</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q096-treated-in-concept-superstitious-observance-st-ii-ii-q096-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q096.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The magic art is both unlawful and futile. It is unlawful, because the means it employs for acquiring knowledge have not in themselves the power to cause science, consisting as they do in gazing certain shapes, and muttering certain strange words, and so forth</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q096" target="st.ii-ii.q096.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q096</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.96 — Superstition in observances</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q096.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.96 a.1 — Observances for acquiring knowledge, which are prescribed by the magic art</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q096.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not unlawful to practice the observances of the magic art. A thing is said to be unlawful in two ways. First, by reason of the genus of the deed , as murder and theft : secondly, through being di</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q096" target="st.ii-ii.q096.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q096</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.96 — Superstition in observances</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q096.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.96 a.2 — Observances for causing alterations in certain bodies</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q096.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that observances directed to the alteration of bodies, as for the purpose of acquiring health, or the like, are lawful. It is lawful to make use of the natural forces of bodies in order to produce their pro</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q096" target="st.ii-ii.q096.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q096</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.96 — Superstition in observances</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q096.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.96 a.3 — Observances practiced in fortune-telling</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q096.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that observances directed to the purpose of fortune-telling are not unlawful. Sickness is one of the misfortunes that occur to man . Now sickness in man is preceded by certain symptoms, which the physician </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q096" target="st.ii-ii.q096.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q096.contains.st.ii-ii.q096.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q096</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.96 — Superstition in observances</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q096.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.96 a.4 — Wearing sacred words at the neck</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q096.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not unlawful to wear divine words at the neck. Divine words are no less efficacious when written than when uttered. But it is lawful to utter sacred words for the purpose of producing certain eff</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
