<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097" target="concept.temptation_of_god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q097.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q097.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 — The temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q097-treated-in-concept-temptation-of-god-st-ii-ii-q097-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Properly speaking, to tempt is to test the person tempted. Now we put a person to the test by words or by deeds . By words, that we may find out whether he knows what we ask, or whether he can and will grant it: by deeds , when, by what we do, we probe another</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097" target="st.ii-ii.q097.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 — The temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q097.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.97 a.1 — In what the temptation of God consists</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the temptation of God does not consist in certain deeds wherein the result is expected from the power of God alone. Just as God is tempted by man so is man tempted by God , man , and demons . But when </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097" target="st.ii-ii.q097.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 — The temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q097.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.97 a.2 — Is it a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not a sin to tempt God . For God has not commanded sin . Yet He has commanded men to try, which is the same as to tempt , Him: for it is written ( Malachi 3:10 ): "Bring all the tithes into the s</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097" target="st.ii-ii.q097.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 — The temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q097.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.97 a.3 — To what virtue is it opposed?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the temptation of God is not opposed to the virtue of religion. The temptation of God is sinful , because a man doubts God , as stated above ( Article 2 ). Now doubt about God comes under the head of u</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097" target="st.ii-ii.q097.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q097.contains.st.ii-ii.q097.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 — The temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q097.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.97 a.4 — Its comparison with other vices</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the temptation of God is a graver sin than superstition . The greater sin receives the greater punishment. Now the sin of tempting God was more severely punished in the Jews than was the sin of idolatr</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097.a001" target="concept.temptation_of_god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a001.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a001.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 a.1 — In what the temptation of God consists</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q097-a001-treated-in-concept-temptation-of-god-st-ii-ii-q097-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Properly speaking, to tempt is to test the person tempted. Now we put a person to the test by words or by deeds . By words, that we may find out whether he knows what we ask, or whether he can and will grant it: by deeds , when, by what we do, we probe another</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097.a002" target="concept.temptation_of_god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a002.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a002.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 a.2 — Is it a sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q097-a002-treated-in-concept-temptation-of-god-st-ii-ii-q097-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ), to tempt a person is to put him to a test. Now one never tests that of which one is certain . Wherefore all temptation proceeds from some ignorance or doubt , either in the tempter (as when one tests a thing in order to know its</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097.a003" target="concept.temptation_of_god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a003.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a003.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 a.3 — To what virtue is it opposed?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q097-a003-treated-in-concept-temptation-of-god-st-ii-ii-q097-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As clearly shown above ( II-II:81:5 ), the end of religion is to pay reverence to God . Wherefore whatever pertains directly to irreverence for God is opposed to religion. Now it is evident that to tempt a person pertains to irreverence for him: since no one p</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q097.a004" target="concept.temptation_of_god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a004.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q097.a004.treated_in.concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q097.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.97 a.4 — Its comparison with other vices</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.temptation_of_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Temptation of God</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q097-a004-treated-in-concept-temptation-of-god-st-ii-ii-q097-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q097.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Among sins opposed to religion, the more grievous is that which is the more opposed to the reverence due to God . Now it is less opposed to this reverence that one should doubt the divine excellence than that one should hold the contrary for certain. For just</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.treated_in.concept.perjury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q098.treated_in.concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Hence falsehood directly annuls the end of an oath : and for this reason, that perversity in swearing, which is called perjury, takes its species chiefly from falsehood. Consequently falsehood is essential to perjury.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="st.ii-ii.q098.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.1 — Is falsehood necessary for perjury?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not necessary for perjury that the statement confirmed on oath be false . As stated above ( II-II:89:3 ), an oath should be accompanied by judgment and justice no less than by truth . Since there</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="st.ii-ii.q098.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.2 — Is perjury always a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that not all perjury is sinful . Whoever does not fulfil what he has confirmed on oath is seemingly a perjurer. Yet sometimes a man swears he will do something unlawful ( adultery , for instance, or murder </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="st.ii-ii.q098.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.3 — Is it always a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that not all perjury is a mortal sin . It is laid down (Extra, De Jurejur, cap. Verum): "Referring to the question whether an oath is binding on those who have taken one in order to safeguard their life and</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="st.ii-ii.q098.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.4 — Is it a sin to enjoin an oath on a perjurer?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that he who demands an oath of a perjurer commits a sin . Either he knows that he swears truly , or he knows that he swears falsely . If he knows him to swear truly , it is useless for him to demand an oath</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098.a001" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a001.treated_in.concept.perjury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a001.treated_in.concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 a.1 — Is falsehood necessary for perjury?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-a001-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Hence falsehood directly annuls the end of an oath : and for this reason, that perversity in swearing, which is called perjury, takes its species chiefly from falsehood. Consequently falsehood is essential to perjury.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098.a002" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a002.treated_in.concept.perjury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a002.treated_in.concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 a.2 — Is perjury always a sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-a002-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">so doing one implies either that God ignores the truth or that He is willing to bear witness to a falsehood. Therefore perjury is manifestly a sin opposed to religion, to which it belongs to show reverence to God .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
