  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q100.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.100 a.1 — What is simony?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q100.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that simony is not "an express will to buy or sell something spiritual or connected with a spiritual thing." Simony is heresy , since it is written (I, qu. i [Can. Eos qui per pecunias.]): "The impious here</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q100" target="st.ii-ii.q100.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q100.contains.st.ii-ii.q100.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q100.contains.st.ii-ii.q100.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q100</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.100 — Simony</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q100.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.100 a.2 — Is it lawful to accept money for the sacraments?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q100.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not always unlawful to give money for the sacraments . Baptism is the door of the sacraments , as we shall state in the III:68:6 ; III:73:3 . But seemingly it is lawful in certain cases to give m</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q100" target="st.ii-ii.q100.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q100.contains.st.ii-ii.q100.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q100.contains.st.ii-ii.q100.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q100</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.100 — Simony</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q100.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.100 a.3 — Is it lawful to accept money for spiritual actions?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q100.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It seems that it is lawful to give and receive money for spiritual actions. The use of prophecy is a spiritual action. But something used to be given of old for the use of prophecy , as appears from 1 Samuel 9:7-8 , and </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q100" target="st.ii-ii.q100.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q100.contains.st.ii-ii.q100.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q100.contains.st.ii-ii.q100.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q100</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.100 — Simony</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q100.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.100 a.4 — Is it lawful to sell things connected with spirituals?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q100.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem lawful to receive money for things annexed to spiritual things. Seemingly all temporal things are annexed to spiritual things, since temporal things ought to be sought for the sake of spiritual things. If, </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
